article.headline: L.A. rallies despite Leslie fouling out

images.name: Leslie_Lisa 052904 372x224
images.caption: The Sparks' Lisa Leslie gets focused the day before a game.

article.linkText: Sparks top Shock in WNBA finals rematch
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- The Detroit Shock were presented with
WNBA championship rings and watched a banner go to the rafters
before their home opener.

Then, they blew a big second-half lead.

Nikki Teasley scored 12 of her 15 points after halftime to lead
the Los Angeles Sparks to a 63-60 comeback win over Detroit on
Saturday in a rematch of last year's WNBA finals.

The Shock knocked off the two-time defending champion Sparks
last September to win the league title, a year after almost moving
or folding.

"If we would've done that last year, we'd be three-time
champions," Los Angeles coach Michael Cooper said. "The one thing
we did was stay mentally tough, even when we were down."

The Sparks rallied to win after trailing by 13 points with more
than 12 minutes left, even though their star, Lisa Leslie, was on
the bench for the final 2:35.

After Leslie fouled out with 12 points, 14 rebounds and three
blocks, Los Angeles scored 12 straight points to take a 63-57 lead
with 17 seconds left.

Detroit's Swin Cash made a 3-pointer with 6.8 seconds to go,
then Mwadi Mabika missed two free throws to set up a chance for
Detroit to force overtime. But Deanna Nolan missed a 3-pointer just
before the buzzer.

"It's frustrating," said Ruth Riley, who had just six points
before fouling out. "We made a lot of mental mistakes at the end
of the game. We can't make the mental errors that we made against
good teams like L.A.

"We were up by a lot and we needed to focus on maintaining that
lead, and extending it."

Cash scored 17 points, and Nolan had 16.

Mabika contributed 12 points, including a 16-foot jumper with
46.6 seconds left that gave the Sparks their first lead since they
were ahead 12-11. Tamecka Dixon added 11 points, including a
3-pointer that tied the game at 57 with 1:33 left.

"We blew a few defensive assignments," Shock coach Bill
Laimbeer said. "We left a couple players open that we probably
shouldn't have."

The Shock scored four points -- on a free throw and Cash's
3-pointer -- in the last 5:03.

"We needed this win more than anything," Mabika said. "I
think we played great defense in the last five minutes."

With league president Val Ackerman among 12,841 at the game and
a network audience watching, the game had an exciting ending after
an awful start.

Los Angeles missed 17 of its first 18 shots, but needed to make
just two straight baskets to take the lead midway through the first
half.

Detroit led 32-22 at halftime and 48-35 midway through the
second half. Los Angeles went on a 11-2 run to start its
game-winning rally.
